@article{Josepovits1989,
abstract = {The present approach to modelling the development of insensitivity to fungicides involves 16 independent variables relating to the pathogen and fungicides. Factors included in the model described here ensure that it is more sensitive to dose-activity functions, the degradation of fungicide residues and the logistic function of the fungal growth. The comparison of different strategies against the build-up of resistance is made on the basis of the logarithmic increase of the resistance frequency during one period of treatment. Moreover, the model describes the gradual shift of the average EC50 value of the whole population when the frequency distributions of the sensitivities of sub-populations are overlapping, thus providing an epidemiological approach to the directional selection. Using this model for the choice of the best anti-resistance strategies, additional conclusions can be drawn compared with those from earlier models. Parameters of crucial importance not previously taken into account are the slopes the slopes of the dose-activity functions of the fungicides applied. Delaying the outbreak of resistance either by combined or alternating use of fungicides is more successful when the slope of the dose-activity function of the at-risk fungicide is steep. The delaying effect of mixtures, being more advantageous than that of alternating treatments in most cases, is rendered less effective at low values of the slope of the activity functions of both fungicides. A partner systemic fungicide restricts any increase in resistance frequency to a greater extent than does a contact fungicide, when used in mixtures; however, the reverse is true for alternating treatments. {\textcopyright} 1989.},
